rules_primary: If X.AI Corp sues Apple Inc. before Jan 1, 2026, then the market resolves to Yes.
rules_secondary: A lawsuit or some other formal adversarial legal process (such as pre-complaint discovery or an arbitration claim) is encompassed by the Payout Criterion.

rules_primary: If Comerica is officially removed from the S&P 500, or it is announced that it will be removed, before Jan 1, 2026, then the market resolves to Yes.
rules_secondary: An announcement by the index provider that the company will be removed is sufficient for resolution, even if the actual removal occurs after the deadline. Removal includes deletion due to eligibility criteria failures, mergers where the company ceases to exist independently, bankruptcy, delisting, or index rebalancing that excludes the company. Temporary suspensions, watchlist additions, or weight changes without removal do not qualify. For companies with multiple share classes, all classes must be removed. If the company is removed and then re-added before the deadline, the market still resolves to Yes.

rules_primary: If Cracker Barrel officially decides to revert, reverse, or substantially undo its rebranding before Oct 1, 2025, then the market resolves to Yes.
rules_secondary: A rebranding reversal requires official announcement by company leadership stating they will return to the previous brand name, logo, or corporate identity. This includes SEC filings indicating a formal change back to the previous name, public statements describing the decision as a reversal or acknowledgment of unsuccessful rebranding, or complete replacement of new branding with the previous version. Minor tweaks, temporary nostalgia campaigns, statements of regret without action, or use of old branding for specific product lines do not qualify. If the company is acquired or undergoes major restructuring before the deadline, the market resolves to No unless the resulting entity explicitly reverses the rebranding.
